# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1855-fiji-expedition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The **Fiji Expedition of 1840** was an exploring and surveying expedition, which itself was a part of the wider United States Exploring Expedition (a.k.a. the **Wilkes expedition** or the **U.S.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.**) that occurred from May 4 to August 11, 1840.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It produced several scientific and cultural breakthroughs in realms such as cartography, oceanography, volcanology, anthropology, ethnography, ethnology, philology, linguistics, geology, taxonomy, trade, diplomacy, toponymy, epidemiology, pathology and Christian missionary work.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It also was known for two separate punitive expeditions against separate groups of Fijians.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. under the command of Lieutenant Charles Wilkes had just discovered that Antarctica was a continent, and finished surveying Wilkes Land.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes was facing a significant deadline.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was originally given a deadline of 3 years to conduct the necessary research for all the allotted study location goals for the expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Unfortunately for him he only had two months to conduct the studies for Fiji expedition, then he would immediately have to journey to the Columbia river expeditions to finish the rest of the studies for the rest of the year.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If Wilkes did not, the sailors' and marines' enlistment service would expire, and the expedition's future would have been put in jeopardy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This situation put Wilkes under immense pressure.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As it was, besides the Columbia river expedition, the Fiji expedition was considered the most paramount research destination for several reasons.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] New England merchants and whalers frequented Fiji for its whale and sandalwood, and competed with the British and the French for the bêche-de-mer populations to sell in China.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Fiji possessed many uncharted reefs, rocks, and currents, with a culture well known for its cannibalism (in fact for a while Fiji was also known as the Cannibal Isles) and a noted penchant for dragging boats to shore and killing all on board.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] No dependable navigation charts existed, and in the 12 years prior to 1840, 8 ships (5 of them being American) had been destroyed in the area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] These conditions made travel to and around these Islands so precarious, the East India Marine Society of Salem, Massachusetts, United States had petitioned the federal government for local charts for sailors navigating these waters.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Although surveying was the primary reason for the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. also brought along a group of scientists which were also deployed for the Fiji expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now that the Antarctic discoveries were finished, Wilkes' fleet traveled to Sydney, Australia, then to the Bay of Islands, New Zealand, and finally they rendezvoused at Tongatapu, in Tonga, and prepared for their next mission in Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes had already had his four ships refitted at Sydney.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His current fleet at the time of the Fiji expedition consisted of Wilkes' flagship the USS *Vincennes* (sloop-of-war, 780 tons, 18 guns), the USS *Peacock* (sloop-of-war, 650 tons, 22 guns), the USS *Porpoise* (brig, 230 tons, 10 guns), and the USS *Flying Fish* (schooner, 96 tons, 2 guns).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Furthermore, Wilkes had at least a dozen gigs, cutters, and whaleboats prepared for travel against the hazardous reefs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes' fleet set sail out of Nukuʻalofa on May 4, 1840.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He dispatched the *Porpoise* under Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold to the Lau Group of the Fiji Islands, while the rest of the fleet went to the Koro Sea.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The 3 ships headed for the Island of Ovalau, but by the morning of May 7, the *Flying Fish* under the command of Lieutenant George Sinclair went missing, after it got caught on a reef.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes pressed on with the *Peacock* and the *Vincennes* and anchored by the village Levuka.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon Wilkes arrival, a white shipwrecked survivor of the Oneo a Nantucket man named David Whippey and one of his sons paddled up to the *Vincennes.* Whippey was what was called a beachcomber, which in this context meant a "tame white man" to the Fijians.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was a sort of mercenary, military advisor, and translator.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The earliest beachcomber Charlie Savage and those like him taught Fijians how to use fire arms.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This revolutionized Fijian warfare, and they were greatly valued by war chiefs, who rewarded them with riches and women.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey had risen to the title of "Mata-ki-Bau" (the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes arranged for Whippey to have him meet the chief or "Tu'i" of Levuku.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes bestowed several gifts upon the chief, who in gratitude and with Whippey's aid sent a message to Tanoa high King *Vunivalu* of Bau (called "Old Snuff by the local whites) and head of the notorious Lasakau sea warriors, and asked to meet with him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a messenger was sent, Whippey took Wilkes and 25 of his officers and naturalists (including the commander of the *Peacock* Lieutenant William L.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson and Navy Geographer and passed midshipman Henry Eld), along with an entourage of natives, on a tour and hike of Mount Nadelaiovalau.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At the top of the mountain Wilkes and his scientists could clearly see the surrounding area including nearby reefs and other nearby landmarks.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The group set out right away making charts, sketches, measurements for recording, and collecting plant and animal specimens.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 8 Wilkes deployed two surveying parties on boats.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One was to be led by Lieutenant James Alden Jr. who would leave Ovalau to explore the northern shore of Viti Levu Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The second boat was led by Lieutenant George F.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons, who in turn scouted the south shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave the officer further orders that after exploring their respective shores that they should assemble at the Island of Malolo which was to the west of Viti Levu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day Lieutenant Sinclair arrived with the *Flying Fish* at Levuka and reported to Wilkes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 11 Wilkes decided to build an observatory of tents, houses, and a small research garden.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was situated 30 feet above the beach on a peak near Levuku village, and above Vi Tonga village as a forward operating center for the Fiji Expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The observatory was erected on May 11, with guards surrounding the perimeter.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 12, Chief Tanoa arrived in a finely decorated 100 foot, double hulled, outrigger canoe with a sail and a 40-man crew.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He boarded the Vincennes and through Whippey was able to negotiate a trade deal between Bau and the United States.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A few days later, Wilkes received Seru Epenisa Cakobau the son and crown prince of Tanoa, who further cemented bonds of the Bau nation and the expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Seru would one day come to unite the Kingdoms of Bau, Rewa, and Naitasiri into the short lived Kingdom of Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Tanoa was the King of Bau, he exercised the greatest influence among all the other kingdoms of the islands of Fiji, Tui Levuku was in charge of Ovalau Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With the aid of Whippey, Tui Levuku helped the Americans maintain their supply lines, trade with Levuku village, and receive information through the first six weeks of the Fiji expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a few says an Irish beachcomber named Paddy O'Connell entered Wilkes, tent on Ovalu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell attempted to hire himself out to Wilkes, but Wilkes dismissed him at first.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, a single story caught his interest.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell informed Wiles that he was a witness to the murder of several of the crew of the American bêche-de-mer merchant ship the *Charles Doggett* in August 1834, on Ono Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes learned that a Fijian chief named Veidovi was the man who organized the attack.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] According to O'Connell he was a crewman of the *Charles Doggett* when the incident occurred.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In this instance Captain Bachelor of the *Charles Doggett* made a contract with a chief named Veidovi for *bêche-de-mer* on Rewa.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the *Charles Doggett* reached Rewa, it was agreed that a minor chief would willingly be taken hostage for the protection of the Westerners while they set up a *bêche-de-mer* house on shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the chief feigned sickness and was allowed to return to shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the minor chief returned with Veidovi and some of his men and asked for medicine at the *bêche-de-mer* house.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mate, eight other men, and a boy came ashore, all except one were killed, robbed, and the house was house set on fire.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the captain, through O'Connell, was able to negotiate for all the bodies back except an African American crewmate whose body was eaten.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later O'Connell became a beachcomber and discovered that while Veidovi was the primary perpetrator of this attack, the other chiefs of Rewa and especially Veidovi's kin endorsed the killings.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon hearing this story Wilkes became angry and sent O'Connell to Lieutenant Hudson on the *Peacock* to arrest Veidovi.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell met Hudson and gave him Wilkes' orders.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair of them set out for Rewa in Viti Levu where Veidovi lived.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was there that Hudson eventually met with King Kania or Roko Tui Dreketi/King of Rewa and Methodist missionaries of the English Wesleyan Mission who helped him get the lay of the land.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After assessing the political landscape, Hudson quickly concocted a plan to trap Veidovi.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 21 Hudson invited the King Kania and his three brothers on board the *Peacock* to a welcoming reception.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Between 70 and over 100 local Fijians showed up along with the Tui Dreketi himself, but Veidovi was noticeably absent.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson lured the native royals into his cabin with an offering of a meal and then called for battle stations.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The royals were split away from their retainers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson promised mercy to the chiefs in exchange for them delivering Veidovi to them, and causing no harm to the local missionaries.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a spout of protest the King Kania agreed, and two of the chiefs brothers were released to arrest Veidovi dead or alive.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The following day Veidovi arrived and agreed to go quietly in exchange for the freedom of his family and their families respectively.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson took Veidovi to his personal cabin for interrogation and Veidovi openly conceded to orchestrating the *Charles Doggett* killings.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi explained that he lured the mate of the ship into a trip and feigned a friendly greeting to the mate of the ship.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then his men seized the mate and clubbed him to death, and then proceeded to kill more of the ship hands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi added that his motivations were to acquire firearms and that he was only following his culture in that "...he had only followed the Fegee customs and done what his people had often done before.".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson decided to punish Veidovi by forcing him to travel with the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and then live in America for a few years, where he would learn to be civilized and not kill white people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi was dismayed, since as a chief he had 55 wives and numerous children that he would have to leave behind.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson then headed for Kadavu Island where it was said more of the perpetrators of the attack on the *Charles Doggett* resided.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, the wind was against him, and suffering for a lack of time in his other duties for the expedition, Hudson satisfied himself with the capture of Veidovi and returned to Levuka.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Word traveled fast of Veidovi's capture, it spread to the village of Levuka, and then to Wilkes himself.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey and Tui Levuku soon caught wind of a plot to capture Wilkes in order to entice and exchange of prisoners (Wilkes for Veidovi).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The suspected perpatrtors would have been King Tanoa who was allies with King Kania.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the Mountains of Ovalau resided the Livoni tribe who were allied with Tanoa.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes remained armed, furnished himself an escort, he ordered 40 men to reinforce the observatory.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes then took Seru hostage on board the *Vincennes*, repositioned the guns of the *Vincennes* to a more defensible position.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes also brought his dog Sydney with him (which terrified the natives), and an attempted kidnapping never materialized.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In early June, a British expedition consisting of the HMS Sulphur (1826) HMS Starling (1829)) commanded by Captain Edward Belcher arrived in Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was conducting his own separate surveying expedition and had just come from the Vavaʻu island group in Tonga.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher traveled to Rewa where the Sulphur had lost a rudder from hitting a reef.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After Belcher's expedition encountered other members of the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and through messengers, Wilkes gave Belcher a spare rudder from the fleet.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, Wilkes came to meet Belcher aboard his ship, and they spoke together in Belcher's cabin.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, despite Wilkes' goodwill in offering Belcher an extra rudder, Belcher was less than pleased to see him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was required to pay port charges due to the trade deal that he had set up between the U.S. and chief Tanoa.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The meeting did not accomplish much, although Wilkes found out that Belcher had explored the Columbia River the year before in 1839, and based on Belcher's descriptions Wilkes believed he would definitely need to extend the length of the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The two parted cordially and Belcher and his ships later sailed to Vanuatu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Chief Tui Levuku decided to honor the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. with a traditional Club dance/Meke called the Meke I Wau or Meke Mada on June 24 at Levuku village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Over a hundred Fijians and their chiefs from Levuku and other nearby villages attended.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans were directed to the Mbure/temple, or spirit-house, which had an elevated platform where they could more easily observe the festivities.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The location overlooked the village from where they observed a low square stone wall on the opposite end of the street.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On one end many Fijians sat down awaiting the performance and on the opposite were several Fijian musicians.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually a "Feejee Clown" emerged in the center of the crowd, and began to galivant and dance wildly, to the delight and laughter of all.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown's body was completely enveloped with green and brown leaves and several vines, except for his face to which he wore a mask.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes stated that to him the mask looked somewhat like the face of a bear.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mask was painted black on one half and orange on the other.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown danced with one large club in one hand and a shorter one on the other.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the clown performed, the musicians began to play with hand claps, sticks, and bamboo joints which made a soft drumming sound.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Roughly 100 club dancers were waiting behind a rock until they were ready.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they emerged in a column of two and began to proceed down the street at a slow three step pace.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They all wore the white *I-sala* turban typically worn by priests and chiefs as well as a white Masi tapa cloth to cover themselves.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Their sala were decorated with flowers and vines, and their faces were painted in various patterns of black and vermillion.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the dance columns advanced they split up from two columns to three and then to four and danced and swung their clubs in a variety of motions and poses.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They danced into the square and joined the clown and the musicians.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The dancers began singing with the musicians and their dances became more rapid and volatile, before they concluded their song and dance with a loud cry of "Wha---hoo".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the presentation had concluded the dancers laid their clubs down in a pile before the Americans as a gift to them, but they expected to receive gifts in return.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day Wilkes gave gifts on behalf of the expedition to Chief Tui Levuku so that he might distribute them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after the end of the club dance festival, Wilkes decided to pack up the observatory and move on to other areas of the Fijian Islands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Before the expeditions departure the purser Robert Waldron purchased and donated land for the construction of a Methodist mission school, with both a school house and chapel led by John Hunt.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following this, the *Vincennes* departed on the 28th of June, to survey the hot springs of Savusavu on the Island of Vanua Levu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Peacock* had several accidents associated with or on it during this expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At Vita Levu the ship sustained considerable, but non fatal damages to its hull.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While one of the Peacocks cutter boats had overturned and sank.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point one man lost three fingers to an anchor chain.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On another occasion a man accidentally shot off his index finger.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A third sailor nearly had his leg entirely detached.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, another sailor had an accident while winding the capstan and broke his ribs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, perhaps the worst accident occurred on June 29 when 2nd mate Joseph Baxter of the *bêche-de-mer* *Leonidas* unwittingly placed a gunpowder cartridge under his shirt while preparing to fire a cannon (for non offensive purposes).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A spark flew off from the igniter and hit the cartridge the man was carrying which exploded over three pounds of gunpowder, and the man was badly charred from the ordeal.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Baxter was later transferred to the Peacock for medical attention.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He confessed that he was a French man whose real name was Vincent Boudet.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] During one occasion of the expedition the *Peacock* was off the coast of Tavea when a chief and his wife and an escort of three canoes approached the ship.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hoping to antagonize the crew, the natives explained that they had captured three prisoners from an enemy village and had "roasted them and eaten part!".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They displayed a piece of one of the bodies that had been preserved in plantain leaves to show the crew.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they produced a half gnawed on skull to be exhibited.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crew also noticed one native eating an eyeball, with flesh dangling from his mouth.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Some of the men vomited at this spectacle.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the Waldron bought the skull to be added to the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s artifact collection in exchange for some cloth.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] William Brackenridge the horticulturalist and Charles Pickering the naturalist teamed up to make several discoveries together while at Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With their mutual cooperation, they discovered over 650 different plant species.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included a new species of tomato and poison ivy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Pickering made the discovery that if the science team did not bring anything that appeared valuable to the natives, they could travel about the Islands without great fear of danger or harassment.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This gave them ample time an opportunity to conduct their research.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And Brackenridge, for his part, found the last existing variant of sandalwood on Fiji, which up until that point was thought to have been extinct from over harvesting.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Horatio Hale, the teams' philologist and anthropologist, documented over 5,600 words in the Fiji language and documented their craftsmanship in producing various canoes, dwellings, and pottery.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] James Dwight Dana the team's geologist made a titanic discovery in his field.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He proved Charles Darwin's theory of subsidence, which Darwin had spoken about publicly, but was formally addressed in his book *The Structure and Distribution of Coral Reefs*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the theory of subsidence after a volcanic Island is formed and after a lengthy period of time a fringing reef forms along the edges or "fringes" of the Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After that and given more time the Island begins to erode and sink and a lagoon begins to form around the island and the fringing reef becomes a barrier reef.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then after further erosion and sinking over time the island sinks into the sea and only the reef and lagoon it forms remains becoming an atoll.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Darwin at first thought he could not adequately prove his theory, but Dana proved it by finding all 3 stages of reef formations on the islands of Cicia, Matuku, and Nanuku.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s surgeons was able to study a number of local diseases endemic to Fiji on Ovalau, as well as the natives methods for treating them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these diseases included a disease the Fijians of the time called "dthoke" which has similarities to both lupus and yaws, and may be mistaken for secondary stage syphilis.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another was a Fijian form of influenza called the "dandy cough" that the natives believe spread and mutated through contact with contact from white people, or as the Fijian's called them "Papalangi".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox believed this influenza may have come from an influenza epidemic that had spread in the USA a few years before the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox recorded reports from many local whites that about a tenth of the Fijian population had died during that time.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 11th, the *Vincenees*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* were surveying in Bua Bay, Bua, Vanua Levu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes dispatched, Lieutenant Oliver Hazard Perry Jr.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] (of the Perry Family) and passed midshipman Samuel R.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox 20 miles southeast, to lead a two cutter survey to chart Solevu bay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair and their crews had been stuck in the bay by a storm for numerous days, with dwindling supplies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the boats were anchored a group of natives taunted them threateningly from the beach.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually their food ran out and both Perry and Knox felt compelled to escape.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The winds blew hard as the crew made for the shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon disembarking the boat, the sailors were encircled by several natives with clubs, spears, and a small amount of firearms.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews gunpowder was wet and so if it came down to a fight the crew would need to resort to hand-to-hand combat.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in an unprecedented move by Western accounts the chief in charge of the natives took pity on the explorers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox and his men swam back to Perry's boat, which became overloaded.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As night fell, the natives lit fires on the beach and occasionally took pot shots at Perry and his men.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the cover of night, the natives stealthily began diving and swimming to the boat, and attempted to either lift the anchor or cut the anchor chain to drag the boat ashore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The sailors began firing into the water, and eventually were able to capture two of the tribesmen who swam to the boat and made an effort to appear to be allies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry suspected them as spies and so arrested them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out they were both chiefs one of high rank and one of low rank.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon taking these men hostage, the natives on the shore made no more attempts to go after the boat that night.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was supposed that they feared the death of their chiefs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When morning came Perry made a second attempt to escape the bay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This time he attempted to maneuver his cutter around the shallow reefs and into the open ocean.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Natives, realizing what Perry was attempting to accomplish, assembled around the edges of the reef.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point the boat struck a reef and took on water.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men attempted to bail and keep their distance from the natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry was able to escape with his crew and prisoners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 12, Perry met with the *Vincennes*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* which had all rendezvoused at Bua Bay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After learning what had happened, Wilkes assembled 11 boats, 80 men, and the *Flying Fis*h to exact retribution, and retrieve the stolen cutter.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The flotilla arrived in the afternoon at low tide.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the waters were shallow a mudflat had formed between Wilkes' ships and the stolen cutter.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes met with the chiefs representatives and used Whippey as a translator.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes commanded the natives to return the boat and all items that were in it.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were intimidated as up until this point in Fijian history there was never before a time when so many westerners had gathered threatening war.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The chief returned the boat, but did not return the boats equipment and belongings of the crew.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Outraged Wilkes landed most of his men armed with muskets, but remained on a gig from which he would direct a Congreve rocket.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes ordered the burning of Solevu village and the politically linked nearby village of Tye.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Combined the fighters of these villages were between 150 and 200 warriors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, both the warriors and the populace fled into the hills and Wilkes fired rockets into the village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The villages were destroyed, but due to the simplicity of the villages' material, the structures would be repaired in a few weeks.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Aside from loss or damage to property no side suffered any casualties.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following the burning of the villages, and in an act of good will, Wilkes released the two captured chiefs and bestowed them with valuable gifts.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His logic was that they came bearing friendship and aid to Perry's crew.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was also done to demonstrate to the natives that hostility to Americans (and white people in general) would be met with vengeance, and cordiality met with reward.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. soon moved on from Solevu to the Mamanuca Islands to continue their survey mission, while the Vincennes and Peacock deployed to Muthuata Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey informed Wilkes that this set of islands was particularly notorious for being perilous to westerners, as the residents of Malolo were noted for being pirates and the worst offenders of attacking foreigners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes acknowledged the danger and made sure his boats were grouped together and well escorted.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He deployed three boats and the *Porpoise* and *Flying Fish* for this mission.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The boats were led by Lieutenants Alden, Emmons, and Joseph Underwood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 22 the squadron reached Drawaqa Island at the southern most end of the Yasawa Islands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent two boats led by Alden and Underwood to the middle of the Mamanucas, the *Porpoise* took the Western side, and the *Flying Fish* and Emmons' cutter took the Western end.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The goal was for all three groups to complete their surveying that day and then assemble together at Malolo Island the next day.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 24, Alden and Underwood finished their surveying without issue, and anchored on the east side of Malolo next to Malolo Lailai for the night.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning Underwood and Alden noticed the *Flying Fish* and Emmons boat anchored in the distant East along Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An hour later, Emmons boat approached Underwood and Alden's.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They inquired for food, but Emmons regrettably told them that the *Flying Fish* was entirely bereft of anymore supplies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This distressed the officers as only a few days ago Wilkes had cut the food rations by a third due to low provision levels, and currently Underwood and Alden's men only had a few yams with them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was decided to try and trade with the local natives for food.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood encountered a Fijian boy chief in the area, who was carrying war clubs which struck him as menacing, and so arrested him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, he found a group of local natives and through a Māori interpreter named John Sac, Underwood negotiated for food.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood was able to negotiate a tentative deal between himself and the natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The village of Malolo was on the Southwest part of the island and the natives proposed making an exchange for a few hogs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in order to get them Underwood would have to accompany the natives and one of the boats would have to sail to the Southwestern part of the island to pick them up.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out that the local chief's son was the man that Underwood had captured.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In light of this, Underwood agreed to travel with the natives to their village provided that the chiefs son stay with his boat as a captive and guarantee of Underwood's safety, and would be released when business was concluded.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood used his own boat (the *Leopard*) as it was smaller than Alden and Emmons cutters and could more easily go over the shallows without getting trapped.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He left all but three of his muskets with the *Porpoise* in order to further reduce weight and increase the ease of travel.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was actually against the standing orders that Wilkes had laid out for safety, but Underwood did not believe that the Fijians were as dangerous as was commonly supposed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood brought Sac with him to translate, along with six other men.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the men stayed with the *Leopard* (commanded by Alden) and their hostage on the beach.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood met a group of natives near the village by a tree.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tree had many throwing and maiming clubs tied to the branches, and two thin hogs next to it.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood tried to barter for the swine, but he was informed that no transaction could be made without the chiefs approval.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After half an hour the chief appeared after returning from a fishing trip.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Chief demanded a musket with ammo and powder in exchange for the hogs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Meanwhile, Alden and his men had waited in their boat a short distance from the shore, however their men were becoming agitated.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tide was coming in and Alden didn't trust the natives as much as Underwood did.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A messenger soon came from Underwood giving him an update of the situation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden sent a message to Underwood to stop negotiating and return to the ship.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent Wilkes' Nephew Midshipman Wilkes Henry (who was named after his Uncle), to deliver the message.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after, a Canoe came up alongside the *Leopard* and began talking to the chief's son.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Fijian attempted to get out of the boat, but Aden pulled him down.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another half an hour passed, and negotiations seemed to be progressing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another messenger from Underwood informed Alden that the chief wanted a hatchet and then the hogs would go to the sailors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden gave the man the hatchet and he ran to give it to Underwood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Not long after Emmons arrived in one of the cutters.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He and his crew had been looking for an area to eat the pigs at the nearby Malolo Lailai island, and began discussing it with Alden.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was sharing with Emmons his anxieties over the negotiations and the chief's son's attempted escape, when the native leaped out of the boat and made for the opposite direction from the village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered one of his men to shoot over the chief's head to entice him to return.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Accounts differ as to what happened next, however when the shot went off.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden and Emmons claimed that the chief's son's escape attempt was a signal for the natives to attack.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While those who were negotiating with the chief claimed that the attack began after the shot was fired.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Either way, the chief shouted that he thought that the sailors on the beach had killed his son, and ordered an assault.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Two Fijians grabbed the musket of one of Underwood's men, named Joseph Clark.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark gripped the musket and then brandished a knife.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He stabbed one native and then bashed another with the muskets' shoulder stock.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, several natives began spilling out of the mangrove bushes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's men began to fire their muskets as they retreated to the two boats.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] About 100 natives began to give chase to the men retreating on the beach and threw spears and throwing clubs at their enemy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes Henry and Underwood covered the retreat.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry was hit by a club and then shot the man who threw it at him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then another native hit him in the back of the head.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry collapsed to the ground with his face in the water, was surrounded by natives, and then stripped.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Joseph Clark was hit by a glancing blow in the mouth and the spear landed in Underwood's left arm.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark shot the man who threw the spear in the head and then another native knocked Clark out with a club.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He fell into the water, but the pain from the salt water on his bloody face soon woke him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark stood up and witnessed Underwood being clubbed in the back of the head.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark attempted to drag Underwood to safety with one arm, and hit away other natives with his other.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Clark was hit twice more and fell down.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got back up when he noticed another native was about to club the unconscious Underwood and stabbed him repeatedly.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark grabbed Underwood again who briefly came to and told him to tell his wife he loved her.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Underwood had his head clubbed in and died.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark was left in a state of shock and delirium.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got up and limped to the rest of the escaping sailors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark's face was covered in blood and dangling flesh and in his absent minded state, he laughed and sang at the natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were perplexed by Clark's actions and stayed clear of him for the rest of the engagement.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Besides Clark, all the men who retreated back to the beach that survived suffered injuries.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Aldan and Emmons saw the fighting on the beach their crews began to row for the shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the other retreating men had assembled at the boats with Alden and Emmons, Alden a handful of men went back to look for Underwood and Henry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They encountered Clark in his delusional state and sent him back to the boats.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had retreated back to their village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Alden and his men found the bodies of both of Underwood and Henry almost completely naked.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's face was smashed beyond recognition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As for Henry, aside from the bruising and his nudity, Henry looked unharmed, but his mourners soon realized that Henry had drowned while unconscious.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the beach, there lay the bodies of ten Fijians from the attack.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of them stirred and was still alive, and in a fit of fury and vengeance the men, shot and stabbed him several times, before cutting off his head.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of the men, wanted to pursue the natives back to their village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] But there were less than two dozen men, and the natives could return at any moment and overwhelm them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden commanded the men make a swift retreat back to the rest of the expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The bodies of Henry and Underwood were gingerly placed in the cutter and covered in jackets to uphold their dignity, and the two boats sailed back to the *Flying Fish*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the bodies were brought on board they were placed in the ships port side and covered with a tarp.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The cadavers were stitched into hammocks, draped in flags, buried on a nearby small island, and hidden out of fear that the natives would dig up and cannibalize the bodies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes named the Island Henry Island after his Nephew (not to be confused with Henry Island (Washington), which he also named after his Nephew later in the expedition).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That night (July 24) Wilkes set up boat patrols commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Eld around Malolo to ensure no native escaped.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It became evident that the natives also expected a counterattack.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fijians in full war paint and equipped with muskets were scattered around the shoreline and would fire pot shots at the boat crews.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews would occasionally fire back, but the natives would take cover and drop prone before a musket ball could hit them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes sent a force of about 70 men and a Fijian scout in 3 divisions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The force was commanded by Lieutenant Ringgold, they landed in Southern Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave orders to kill all men and burn the village, but "spare only the women and the children.".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From there the men began marching to the fortified village of Sualib just outside of where Underwood and Henry were killed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* waited on the coast with their cannons fixed on the shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* was originally going to lead the boats into battle, but it grounded on a sandbar.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the meantime Wilkes organized a small fleet of boats commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Clark whose mission was to search and destroy all hostile escaping canoes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] There other objective was to approach the smaller Arro (sometimes called Yaro) village and neutralize it while Ringgold's force would destroy Sualib and link up with Wilkes flotilla in Arro.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the landing party was disembarking, three canoes appeared and were headed to Malolo Lailai.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and Alden took two boats and pursued them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once they were close enough an interpreter asked the natives where they were from.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native responded that they were from Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed six natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the natives jumped in the water.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered that the rest be taken as prisoners, but his men had bloodlust and shouted "Kill" repeatedly.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One man grabbed a Fijian woman by the hair and was about to slash her with his sword when Alden aimed his pistol at him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was able to reign in his men and together with Emmons, and they captured several men, women, and children, including a chief from Arro village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men were handcuffed and kept captive, but the women and children were released on the beach.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Emmons and Alden were occupied capturing the natives during their engagement, Wilkes proceeded with his boats to Arro.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He found the village deserted, and put it to the flame.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men had gone ahead to join the defense of Sualib and the women and children had fled to the mountains.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes continued on and hoped to reinforce Ringgold at Sualib, but found it destroyed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He doubled back and later met Ringgold at Arro.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ground force landed at 10 A.M. and divided up in to three groups as Wilkes had ordered.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The groups were led by Lieutenants Ringgold, Robert Johnson and Andrew Murray, and included passed midshipman Henry Eld and Alfred Thomas Agate of the science corps.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ringgold gave a short speech and reminded the men to destroy everything except the women and children.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The forces split up into different paths and destroyed farms along the way, before meeting up and surrounded the fort.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort itself was circular, with a 12 foot wide by 6 feet deep ditch/dry moat which they used as a trench, and a ten foot tall coconut tree and whicker palisade on all sides.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had occupied the trench and the palisade edges, and together they either aimed their muskets outside of the trench through small holes in the palisade walls.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of chiefs, recognizable by their white headdresses, commanded the warriors in between the trenches and stockade.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The warriors began to shout obscenities at the oncoming attackers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans fired a Congreve rocket and their muskets at the fort, and the Fijians quickly dashed into the fort.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The enemy retreated, a portion of Johnson's division, without orders stormed the fort.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The attack was spearheaded by Sinclair with a double barrel shotgun.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Sinclair entered the fort he quickly realized that it was a trap.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ditch which had been built outside of the palisades also extended into the interior and was occupied by a large number of natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included women armed with bows who fought with their men.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Retreat for Sinclair and his advance was impractical and decidedly more dangerous than it was worth.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort was purposefully built like a fish weir trap, with a wide opening, but a narrow avenue of escape.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair got shot with an arrow in his lapel, but it only penetrated the fabric of his coat and not the skin.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair's fortune did not stop at his lapel.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans began running up to the palisade and shooting into the village through the small holes the Fijians had previously been using.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Musket fire and Congreve rockets poured into Sualib.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Americans began trickling into the village, in twos, by a narrow bridge, through the gate, and into the fort following Sinclair's example.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point Sinclair shot a chief with his pistol, which turned out to be the chief of Sualib.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Several natives carried the chiefs limp body to a nearby hut.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The battle crept on in a state of havoc for about 15–30 minutes before a Congreve rocket hit the top of a dry roof and caught fire.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native warrior got on to of the roof in an effort to remove the rocket before the fire spread, but he was shot down in a hail of bullets.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fire proliferated and began to engulf the village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The blaze forced the natives to flee the ditch and into American musket fire, which cut them down.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The resulting spectacle was pure pandemonium.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A translator attempted to shout that the women and children would be allowed to escape.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fire and gun smoke were everywhere, children were weeping, pigs were crying, the fire roared, the noise was ear splitting.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans cheered their success and then fell back to a coconut grove, as the village burned.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a half an hour to an hour, the fires had settled to an approachable state, the Americans reentered the village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They soon discovered, that based on the remaining native supplies, the natives had expected a lengthy engagement.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans found piles of hollowed out calabashes filled with water, burnt yams and charred pigs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Discarded muskets, spears, and clubs littered the floor of the ditch.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The weapons were pilled up on a pyre and immolated.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After searching the still standing huts, Underwood's bloody cap was discovered.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Out of the bodies only four or five survived being burnt to ashes including a little girl and the chief of Sualib.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The preservation of the chief's cadaver was soon ended, as with a streak of vengeance, the Americans threw his body into a burning house.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Evidence of the horror that had occurred before was still present to the senses of the Americans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The treeline was pierced by misfired arrows.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The smoke filled the nostrils of the sailors and marines which took on the smell of burnt human flesh, as it approached the heavens in an otherwise blue sky.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was in this setting that the otherwise exhausted combatants decided to rest and refresh themselves on coconuts to quench their thirst.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the men drank, it was discovered that the most significant injury among them was a sailor who suffered a solitary gash on the leg from an arrow.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After the brief respite, the force divided into the marching lines to the nearby village of Arro and burned several houses and farms along the way.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was suspected that most of the surviving villagers were hiding somewhere in the hills.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, they did encounter one native on the way who was instantly bayonetted multiple times to death.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon arriving there, they found that Arro had already been burned down by Wilkes and Alden.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Adding the bayoneted man as a casualty and counting the lowest and highest estimate, approximately 58 to about 88 Fijians had been killed between Arro and Sualib.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The last skirmish that occurred during the battle lasted throughout much of the day.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After midday, Lieutenant Emmons had been tracking five canoes that had been spotted in the morning.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They had escaped Malolo, and were hiding near Malolo Lailai.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Each canoe contained about eight fighters and their sides were reinforced to curb a potential attack.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons was sailing his cutter which was, at this point, only at half its normal capacity.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He had only seven men under his command.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In any case, Emmons made full sail and pulled up alongside the closest canoe.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed several natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and another sailor jumped in the canoe, as Emmons grappled with a spear throwing native, the sailor killed him with a hatchet.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One canoe got away, but the natives in the other canoes jumped overboard.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After they took the plunge, they were either shot, slashed, or axed by the Americans as they swam for the shallows.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons sailed back to the *Porpoise* before midnight.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning it was discovered that the bodies of the natives killed by Emmons and his men were eaten by sharks.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day (July 25, 1840) Wilkes made plans with a declaration to lead a second engagement to kill "Every man on the Island", however an assembly of natives congregated on the beach near the *Flying Fish*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes summoned an interpreter and together they sailed on a gig to shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As Wilkes drew nearer the crowd dispersed, leaving behind a lone native woman to treat with Wilkes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The native offered Wilkes some of Underwood and Henry's clothes, belongings, and a chicken as an offer of peace.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes retrieved the recovered items from his fallen crewmen, but refused the chicken.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was under the impression that according to Fijian tradition, for a nation to be truly conquered the populace of that nation must be present to witness a peace declaration.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Instead Wilkes entreated to the woman, he and his men would meet on a hill in southern Malolo to discuss peace terms with the whole tribe.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If however, the remaining chiefs and peoples of Malolo did not make an appearance, then Wilkes and his men would continue the onslaught.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Around noon, Wilkes and his men climbed the hill, which perfectly overlooked views of the sheer destruction yesterday had delivered.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, at approximately 4 P.M. a column of weeping natives (including 40 men) began to approach the hill.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At first, the native would not go beyond the foot of the hill.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes threatened to wipe them out if they did not climb the hill in an act of contrite submission.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives crawled on their hands and knees up the hill.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An old native man approached Wilkes, spoke for Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He begged for mercy, and declared that his people would never attack white men again.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He admitted his people were conquered and had only about 80 surviving men left.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He also offered Wilkes two young native women in reparation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave a speech through a translator about the power of "white" people and that if a similar attack ever happened again, then he would drive the people of Malolo to extinction.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] July 26, Wilkes and his men went to what was left of Arro village and had the people fill casks of water for his vessels.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the morning of July 27, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* sailed off the coast of Arro and 70 natives loaded them with 3,000 gallons of water, 12 pigs, and 3,000 coconuts.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day the natives retrieved Underwood's pocket watch which had melted in the fire, and Henry's glasses.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 31, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* returned to Bua bay where the rest of the fleet was working.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes privately blamed Alden and Underwood for the deaths of Henry and Underwood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In retaliation Wilkes had Underwood's possessions sold at an auction to much protest from the officers, and most notably midshipman James Blair who was the executor of Underwood's freshly written will just prior to the battle of Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes vindictive streak did not appear to end with Underwood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes next turned his anger to chief Veidovi.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From his capture up until the end of the expedition in Fiji, Hudson had been kind to Veidovi and even permitted him to go on deck and speak to the officers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes had Veidovi transferred from the *Peacock* to his flagship the *Vincennes*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now Wilkes kept Veidovi confined to quarters.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Wilkes had the ships barber cut Vincennes hair.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This mortified Veidovi, since his hair marked his status and was important in Fijian culture.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. had ended Wilkes published a book called *Narrative of the United States Exploring Expedition* in 1844.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes in hindsight was mad at Alden for a number of perceived grievances.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these grievances included the idea that Alden was responsible for the deaths of Underwood and Henry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And he wrote about this an his other grievances in his book.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. left Fiji in August and set a course for more surveying and scientific work in Hawaii, before temporary splitting up the expedition to survey Hawaii and other islands in Polynesia such as modern day French Polynesia, the Cook Islands, and the Gilbert Islands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, the expedition surveyed the Columbia River.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] On the return trip the expedition traveled to Wake Island, and returned by way of the Philippines, Borneo, Singapore, Polynesia, and the Cape of Good Hope, reaching New York on June 10, 1842.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While on the surveying expedition for the Columbia river, Wilkes appeared to have loosened his enmity to Veidovi at one point.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He began allowing him on the deck of the *Vincennes*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] A few months later on July 4th 1841 Wilkes and his men landed on Vancouver Island and fired off two howitzers in celebration of the holiday.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] During this occasion Veidovi was allowed to walk on shore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The next year in June, 4th 1842 Veidovi died a few days after landing in New York (possibly from pulmonary tuberculosis), although the Washington Herald inaccurately asserted that Veidovi died from a lack of eating human meat.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Veidovi's death surgeons at the Brooklyn Naval Hospital removed Veidovi's head, pickled it, and then after a time the flesh was removed, and the skull was thereafter labeled Specimen 292 and was featured in the Smithsonian Institution, and became one of the most popular exhibits.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Wilkes' arrival in New York several court martials were organized for the entire Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes had made many enemies in both the Navy, and the government.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He was almost universally despised by his men for many of the actions he took during the expedition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Other officers were charged with various crimes, but Wilkes was charged with 11, and his actions throughout the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. were criticized in the defense of the other officers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his actions during Fiji the Battle of Malolo, Wilkes was charged with illegally attacking the natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes justified his actions by stating "But I felt then as I do now, that the punishment was sufficient and effectual, while it was accompanied, as far as it could be, with mercy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, even the most ardent of Wilkes detractors supported Wilkes on this matter.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Many of them indicated by their words and actions that they hated the natives for killing their friends and desired revenge.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] What's more, Wilkes was able to garner sympathy for the death of his nephew of which it was universally acknowledged that he loved dearly.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ultimately Wilkes was cleared of all charges including his Fiji charges.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The exception was that Wilkes was found guilty of illegally flogging marines and sailors in Hawaii after they refused to work when their enlistments were up.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As a consequence, Wilkes was given a public reprimand.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In 1843, a 22-foot cenotaph obelisk was built in Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge Massachusetts to remember the officers who had fallen in the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] More specifically, the monument memorialized the loss of life in two separate events of the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This included the loss of the USS *Sea Gull* (1838) a schooner that was Captained by Midshipman James W.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Reid with the help of Midshipman Frederick A.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The *Sea Gull* was awaiting resupply from the USS *Relief* (1836), after which she was due to rendezvous with the rest of the fleet at Valparaíso, Chile.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] She was last spotted off Cape Horn at Midnight on 28 April 1839.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] After a while when the *Sea Gull* never returned the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While one side of the obelisk commemorates the memory of the officers of the *Sea Gull*, another preserves the memory of Henry Wilkes and Joseph Underwood killed during the first day of the battle of Malolo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Officers and Scientific Corps. of the expedition took up a collection for their fallen comrades by the end of the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes and his family desired that this monument should be constructed at a cemetery in Brooklyn, New York for the benefit of Henry's mother and sister who lived near by.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, in part due to spite over Wilkes' treatment of them the officers had the monument built in Cambridge close to Underwood's widow.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Specifically the Obelisk reads: "To the memory of Lieutenant Joseph A.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Underwood and Midshipman Wilkes Henry, U.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This cenotaph is erected by their associates, the officers and scientific corps of the U.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Methodist missionary Reverend David Cargill reported to Hudson that because of the arrest of Veidovi, the other chiefs of Rewa became terrified at the prospect of harming white people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And that this show of strength served to aid in both Western trade and missionary work.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his political, translation, and informative aid in the expedition Wilkes made David Whippey the temporary consul of the United States in Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, a more formal consul named John B.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, with Wilkes' recommendation Secretary of State John C.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Calhoun appointed him to vice consul of Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Nancy Shoemaker, she theorizes the combination of the Fijians newfound fear of retribution for attacks against Westerners following the attacks of the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.. combined with Whippey's new position of power provided a lasting impact on Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In that vein of thought, Shoemaker points out that Whippey's new found power complemented his unofficial title as chief of the white men/beachcombers of Levuka and the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] With this fusion of power came a desire for autonomy for both Whippey and the white beachcombers he represented.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Traditionally, the beachcombers were compelled to fight for whichever local chief had them under employment.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, when chief Cakobau of Bau called them up to aid in him waging war against Cakaudrove at Somosomo, the beachcombers refused.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] They claimed they wished to protect their property.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Cakobau became incensed, and was even more so after he lost the war against Cakaudrove.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He feared that directly punishing Whippey and his beachcombers might bring down the wrath of the United States or another western power.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Instead his punishment of the beachcombers was indirect and subtle.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He encouraged other tribes under his domain to steal the beachcombers polygamous wives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He later demanded greater tributes from them and sent arsonists to burn down their homes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The situation became exasperated when in 1843, the beachcombers refused to participate in the Bau–Rewa war.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This time Cakobau exiled the whites and their mixed-race children to Bua and near the village of Solevu that was destroyed by the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, by 1849, Cakobau allowed the beachcombers to return to Levuka.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Trade in Levuka had suffered since the exile.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers were all to often, the most reliable middlemen traders for Fijians and the trade ships that came through Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] To Cakobau's dismay upon the beachcombers return they began to dominate all foreign trade to the exclusion of Cakobau and the Fijian people as a whole.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers under Whippey began defending themselves against small skirmishes or arsons as advanced by Cakobau.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] At this point beachcombers like Whippey, and their mixed families, had begun to transcend from being middleman minorities to autonomous settlers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers at Levuka and elsewhere gradually made moves to separate themselves from the Fijian populace and became a semi independent military and trading power.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The British would later capitalize upon this development, when they took ownership of it in 1874 and made Levuka its first capital.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, according to Shoemaker, it was the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.'s precedent for protection and subsequent retaliation for harm against whites that began the beachcombers move towards autonomy and the later British take over of the islands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. taken as a whole led to several lasting scientific revelations, explorative discoveries, and historical preservations that continue to endure to today.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji expeditions artifacts contributed to the earliest collections for the National Institute for the Promotion of Science, the precursor to what would become the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In addition to the cannibalized skull and the skull of chief Veidovi, an assortment of Fijian weapons had been procured for future display at the institute.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes names the Ringgold Isles after Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Numerous botanical samples were also obtained from Fiji and other lands the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. surveyed, and were placed in the United States Botanic Garden or the Smithsonian Gardens.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Dried plant specimens comprised the core of what is now the **National Herbarium**, an herbarium curated by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji Expedition was also not without its merits, for its contributions to science.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As mentioned previously, Horatio Hale documented 5,600 words in the Fiji language as well as other information of anthological and cultural importance.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Through his studies he produced the book *Ethnography and Philology* (1846), which is said to have laid the foundations of the ethnography of Polynesia, including Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He is often cited as the Father of Polynesian ethnology.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Moreover, the scientists Charles Pickering, William Brackenridge, and William Rich, collectively brought over 50,000 specimens of 10,000 species.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And of the 241 charts that were created during the Ex.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. there was included the first ever complete chart of Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] In October 1855, the United States Navy sent a warship to Fiji during the civil war on the islands.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] They demanded compensation from Seru Epenisa Cakobau, the Vunivalu of Bau and self-proclaimed Tui Viti (King of Fiji), in response to the alleged arson attacks on the American commercial agent in Lautoka, Viti Levu.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] The initial incident that led to the American expedition was the burning in 1849 of the house owned by agent John Brown Williams when it was hit by cannon fire.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] A subsequent incident happened the same year as the expedition when, again, fire was to interrupt Williams's duties.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] Another accidental fire on Nukulau destroyed his store, and some Fijians looted it.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] Boutwell, was sent to monitor the unrest in October, and her crew landed multiple times to protect American interests.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] When Commander Boutwell heard of the incidents involving William's house and store, he demanded US$5,000 in compensation from King Cakobau.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] This initial claim was supplemented by further claims totalling $45,000.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] He gave the natives a deadline and threatened them with a landing party of marines and sailors to capture the king in the island's village if they failed to pay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] Fijian warriors put up some resistance, one American service man was killed, and two were wounded.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] Ultimately the Adams's men were successful in routing a contingent of natives from Lautoka, but Cakobau and the survivors escaped capture.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] Cakobau's claim to be King of Fiji was by no means universally recognised by his fellow-chiefs who jealously guarded the independence of their fiefdoms.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] If he acknowledged the debt, he did not have sufficient funds to pay it, yet if he disclaimed it by saying that it fell under the jurisdiction of another chief, he would jeopardize his claim to the kingship, which he wanted foreign powers to recognise.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] He decided to bide his time, hoping that the Americans were only bluffing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1855-fiji-expedition] An 1858 Fiji expedition, involving the crew of *Vandalia*, achieved clearer results, and the debt itself was not resolved until 1862.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] In 1858, the United States Navy launched an operation on the island of Waya in Fiji following the death of two American traders there.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The Pacific Squadron executed a punitive expedition against the native warriors of Seru Epenisa Cakobau and defeated them in a pitched battle at the village of Somatti.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] In mid-1858, two American citizens on Waya were killed and cannibalized by the natives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] When word of the incident reached the American consulate at Ovalau, the Pacific Squadron sent the *Vandalia*, and the sloop-of-war arrived on 2 October 1858.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The *Vandalia'*s draft was not shallow enough to reach Waya, so Commander Sinclair chartered the schooner *Mechanic* and placed her under the command of veteran Lieutenant Charles Caldwell.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] A force of 10 marines, forty sailors and a 12-pounder howitzer were mustered for the landing on Waya.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] A few Fijian guides and three American merchant sailors also participated.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] One was Captain Josiah Knowles of the *Wild Wave*, a clipper ship wrecked off Oeno Island.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Knowles and 40 others were marooned on the island until being rescued by *Vandalia* and taken to Fiji.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The expedition left Ovalau on 6 October 1858 and sailed west around the northern end of the main island of Viti Levu to Waya.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] During their passage to the island, Lieutenant Caldwell's men heard many stories from towns and villages about the warriors of Waya.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The Wayan chiefs responsible for the deaths of the two American traders also sent a letter: "Do you suppose we have killed the two white men for nothing?
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] No, we killed them and we have eaten them.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] We are great warriors, and we delight in war".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell later wrote, "...and woe to the members of any strange tribe that falls into their hands... to be clubbed to death and eaten is the only alternative for the captive.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] It is not a matter of surprise that the tribes along our route learned with feelings of satisfaction the nature of our expedition".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] At 03:00 on 9 October, the Americans made a landing and marched inland toward the village of Somatti over tropical and mountainous terrain.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] While climbing through the mountains, the 12-pounder was destroyed and left behind when it fell 2,300 feet (700 m) down the side of a hill as the expedition tried to pull it up.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The column reached Somatti in daytime, and over 300 native warriors were in front of the village for defense, clothed in white robes and armed with clubs, rocks, spears, bows, and some muskets.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The Americans had swords and carbine rifles.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Lieutenant Caldwell ordered a flanking maneuver on the left side of the mass of warriors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Routed, the natives dispersed themselves amongst the town or fled into the jungle.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Bartlett, who led a group of sailors, sang "Red, White, and Blue" and let out three cheers before charging and capturing the village.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The crew of the 12-pounder, with no gun to fire, took charge of burning the village, and over 115 huts were destroyed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Marines under Lieutenant Alan Ramsey, providing a rearguard for the sailors, repulsed a final Wayan attack from the jungle after they had regrouped.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] In all fourteen warriors, including the two chiefs, were counted dead after a fierce half-hour battle.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Two marines survived their wounds by musketry, two sailors were hurt badly by rocks, one other marine was hit in the leg with an arrow, and a sailor from *Wild Wave* was hurt as well.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] After the battle the Americans took until 16 October to return to the coast where the *Mechanic* was waiting.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] They stopped at friendly Fijian fishing villages and spread the news of their victory.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell noted that two ramrods and one bayonet were lost during the march, and a large amount of ammunition was used in battle.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1858-fiji-expedition] The lieutenant received much credit for the operation, considered one of the most impressive military campaigns launched by the United States in the South Pacific during the nineteenth century.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The **1892 Coeur d'Alene labor strike** erupted in violence when labor union miners discovered they had been infiltrated by a Pinkerton agent who had routinely provided union information to the mine owners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The response to the labor violence, disastrous for the local miners' union, became the primary motivation for the formation of the Western Federation of Miners (WFM) the following year.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The incident marked the first violent confrontation between the workers of the mines and their owners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Labor unrest continued after the 1892 strike, and surfaced again in the labor confrontation of 1899.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Shoshone County, Idaho area miners organized into several local unions during the 1880s.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Mine owners responded by forming a Mine Owners' Association.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] In 1891, the Coeur d'Alene district shipped ore containing US$4.9 million (~$154 million in 2024) in lead, silver, and gold.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The mine operators got into a dispute with the railroads which had raised rates for hauling ore.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Mine operators also introduced hole-boring machines into the mines.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The new machines displaced single-jack and double-jack miners, forcing the men into new, lower-paid jobs as trammers or muckers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Mine operators found a reduction in wages the easiest way to mitigate increased costs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] After the machines were installed, the mine owners were going to pay the mine workers $3.00 to $3.50 per day, depending upon their specific jobs.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] 12 The operators also increased miners' work hours from nine to ten hours per day, with no corresponding increase in pay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The work week would be seven days long, with an occasional Sunday off for those who did not have pumping duty.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The miners had other grievances; for example, high payments for room and board in company lodging, and check cashing fees at company saloons.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] In 1892, the miners declared a strike against the reduction of wages and the increase in work hours.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The miners demanded that a "living wage"p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] 12 of $3.50 per day be paid to every man working underground—the common laborer as well as the skilled.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] In an era when many unions were AFL craft unions, in which skilled workers frequently looked after their own kind, this was an unusual circumstance—approximately three thousand higher-paid miners standing up for five hundred lower-paid, in this case *common* laborers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] This principle of industrial unionism would animate Western hardrock miners for the next several decades.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] When the union miners walked out of the mines, mining company recruiters enticed replacement workers to Coeur d'Alene during the strike.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] They advertised in Michigan, in some cases touting mining jobs in Montana, mentioning nothing about the strike.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Soon every inbound train was filled with replacement workers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] But groups of armed, striking miners would frequently meet them, and often threatened the workers to not take the jobs during a strike.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The silver-mine owners responded by hiring Pinkertons and the Thiel Detective Agency agents to infiltrate the union and report on strike activity.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Pinkertons and other agents went into the district in large numbers.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Soon there was a significant security force available to protect new workers coming into the mines.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] For a time the struggle manifested as a war of words in the local newspapers, with mine owners and mine workers denouncing each other.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] There were incidents of brawling and arrests for carrying weapons.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Two mines settled and opened with union men, and these mine operators were ostracized by other mine owners who did not want the union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] But two large mines, the Gem mine and the Frisco mine in Burke-Canyon, were operating full scale.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] In July a union miner was killed by mine guards, and the tension between the strikers and the mine owners and their replacement workers grew.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] An undercover Pinkerton agent, soon-to-be well-known lawman, Charlie Siringo, had worked in the Gem Mine as a shoveler.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Using the alias Charles Leon Allison, Siringo joined the Gem Miners' Union, and was elected recording secretary, providing him with access to all of the union's books and records.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] According to Siringo, he had at first turned down the assignment, because his sympathies were with the union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The Pinkerton Agency agreed that he could withdraw from the assignment after he became familiar with the situation, yet Siringo stayed on to complete the one year and two month assignment.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Siringo promptly began to report all union business to his employers, allowing the mine owners to outmaneuver the miners on a number of occasions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Strikers planned to attack a train of incoming replacement workers, so the mine owners dropped them off in an unexpected location.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] When the Gem Union president, Oliver Hughes, ordered Siringo to remove a page from the union record book that recorded plans to flood the mines, the agent mailed that page to the Mine Owners' Association (MOA).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] George Pettibone also confided in Siringo of a planned July uprising to run the non-union workers and mine owners out of the country, and take possession of the mines for the union workers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Siringo was suspected as a spy when the Mine Owners' Association newspaper, the *Barbarian*, published information which obviously came from a member of the union, but Siringo managed to escape capture and certain death.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Siringo's testimony helped convict 18 union leaders, including George Pettibone.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] On Sunday night, July 10, armed union miners gathered on the hills above the Frisco mine.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] More union miners were arriving from surrounding communities.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Strikers opened fire at 5 am on July 11, 1892, and guards and workers in the mill building returned fire.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The guards and strikebreakers inside the mine and mill buildings were prepared for a long standoff, having been warned by Charlie Siringo.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] After three and a half hours of gunfire without casualties, striking miners on the hill above sent a bundle of dynamite down a sluice into the mill, destroying the building and crushing one of the strikebreakers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The rest of the strikebreakers in the wrecked Frisco mill surrendered and were taken to the union hall as prisoners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] After the Helena-Frisco strikebreakers surrendered, the striking miners shifted to the Gem mine, where a similar gunfight took place.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The Gem miners were well-entrenched, but the Gem management, fearing similar destruction of property as took place at the Frisco, ordered the men to surrender.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Three union men, one company guard and one strikebreaker were killed by gunfire before the strikebreakers surrendered.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] At the end of the day, six men were dead, three on each side, and there were 150 strikebreakers and guards held prisoner in the union hall.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] They were put on a train and were told to leave the county.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Minutes after the explosion at the Frisco mine, hundreds of miners converged on Siringo's boarding house.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] But Siringo sawed a hole in the floor, dropped through and covered the hole with a trunk, then crawled for half a block under a wooden boardwalk.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Above him, he could hear union men talking about the spy in their midst.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Siringo escaped, and fled to the wooded hills above Burke-Canyon Creek.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] On the evening of July 11, about 500 strikers left Gem by train to the Bunker Hill mine at Wardner.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The Bunker Hill management was taken by surprise, and the strikers took possession of the ore mill during the night, and put a ton of explosive beneath it.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The next morning they gave the manager the choice of discharging his non-union employees, or having his mill destroyed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] He chose to get rid of the nonunion workforce.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] While these men waited to board a boat at Coeur d'Alene Lake, some striking miners fired again, and at least seventeen non-union workers were wounded.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] More than a hundred of the men decided not to wait for the boat, and they hiked out of the area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The miners considered the battle over and the union issued a statement deploring "the unfortunate affair at Gem and Frisco." Funerals were Wednesday afternoon, July 13.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Three union men and two company men were buried.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The governor declared Martial Law, and ordered in six companies of the Idaho National Guard to "suppress insurrection and violence." Federal troops also arrived, and they confined six hundred miners in bullpens without any hearings or formal charges.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Some were later "sent up" for violating injunctions, others for obstructing the United States mail.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] After the Guard and federal troops secured the area, Siringo came out of the mountains to identify union leaders, and those who had participated in the attacks on the Gem and Frisco mines.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] He wrote that "As I knew all the agitators and union leaders, I was kept busy for the next week or so putting unruly cattle in the 'bull pen', a large stockade with a frame building in the center, for them to sleep and eat in." Siringo then returned to Denver.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] One of the union leaders, George Pettibone, was convicted of contempt of court and criminal conspiracy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Pettibone was sent to Detroit and held until a decision of the Supreme Court released him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The Court concluded that the prisoners were held illegally.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Union members held in jail in Boise, Idaho were also releasedp.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] On May 15, 1893, in Butte, Montana, the miners formed the Western Federation of Miners (WFM) as a direct result of their experiences in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The WFM immediately called for outlawing the hiring of labor spies, but their demand was ignored.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] The WFM embraced the tradition that their organization was born in the Boise, Idaho, jail.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Charlie Siringo was not the only agent to have infiltrated the Coeur d'Alene miners' unions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Anthony Lukas mentions that Thiel Operative 53 had also infiltrated, and had been the union secretary at Wardner.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] One of the demands of the WFM's founding Preamble was the prohibition of armed detectives.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1892-coeur-d-alene-labor-strike] Coeur d'Alene Miners engaged in another confrontation with mine owners in the Coeur d'Alene, Idaho labor confrontation of 1899.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The **Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, labor riot of 1899** was the second of two major labor-management confrontations in the Coeur d'Alene mining district of northern Idaho in the 1890s.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Like the first incident seven years earlier, the 1899 confrontation was an attempt by union miners, led by the Western Federation of Miners to unionize non-union mines, and have them pay the higher union wage scale.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] As with the 1892 strike, the 1899 incident culminated in a dynamite attack that destroyed a non-union mining facility, the burning of multiple homes and outbuildings and two murders, followed by military occupation of the district.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The riot of 1899 resulted from the miners' frustrations with mine operators that paid lower wages, hired Pinkerton or Thiel operatives to infiltrate the union, and the refusal of non-union miners to join or strike.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Angered by wage cuts, Coeur d'Alene area miners conducted a strike in 1892.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The strike erupted in violence when union miners discovered they had been infiltrated by a Pinkerton agent who had routinely provided union information to the mine owners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] After several deaths, the U.S. army occupied the area and forced an end to the strike.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The response to that violence, disastrous for the local miners' union, became the primary motivation for the formation of the Western Federation of Miners (WFM) the following year.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Pro-union sentiment remained strong in the area, and by 1894, most of the mines were unionized, represented by the Knights of Labor.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Violence erupted in the Coeur d'Alene district during the national Pullman railroad strike of 1894.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Union members attacked non-union mines and workers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Forty masked men shot to death John Kneebone, who had testified against union miners in 1892.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Others kidnapped a mine superintendent, and tried to blow up the powder house at the Bunker Hill mine.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Urged by the mine owners, the Idaho governor requested federal troops, supposedly to prevent interruptions in railroad service along the Northern Pacific route through the Coeur d'Alene area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] President Grover Cleveland sent about 700 troops in July 1894.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Major General John Schofield, determined to avoid embroiling his troops in a local labor dispute as they were in 1892, directed that the Army confine its mission to keeping the railroads running, and not take orders from state or local officials.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The Army patrolled the railroad lines, and reported no disturbances or local opposition.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The union members, wanting to avoid another military occupation, stopped the attacks on non-union targets.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The Army repeatedly reported that there were no disturbances of rail transport, and requested permission to withdraw the troops.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The mine owners pressured the Cleveland administration to keep the troops in place.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The mine owners eventually realized that the Army would not expand its mission beyond protecting the railroad, and dropped their opposition to withdrawal of the troops.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The Army units left the Coeur d'Alene in September 1894.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] In December 1894, the Bunker Hill and Sullivan mine shut down rather than agree to the union demand of a uniform wage of $3.50 (~$130.00 in 2025) per day.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The mine reopened in June 1895, with nonunion labor paying $3.00 per day to miners and $2.50 to surface employees and unskilled underground labor.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The company said that whenever the combined prices of lead and silver rose again to a certain point, they would restore the old wage rate.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The Bunker Hill Mining Company at Wardner was profitable, having paid more than $600,000 in dividends.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Miners working in the Bunker Hill and Sullivan mines were receiving fifty cents to a dollar less per day than other miners, which at that time represented a significant percentage of the paycheck.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The properties were the only mines in the district that were not entirely unionized.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] In April 1899, as the union was launching an organizing drive of the few locations not yet unionized, superintendent Albert Burch declared that the company would rather "shut down and remain closed twenty years" than to recognize the union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] He then fired seventeen workers that he believed to be union members and demanded that all other union men collect their back pay and quit.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The strike by the union local at Wardner was not succeeding, and the nearby WFM locals, at Gem, Burke, and Mullan, feared that the other mine owners would cut wages to match those paid at the Bunker Hill mine.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] During the trial, these proved to be only rumors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The other WFM locals agreed to support the strike at Wardner.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The officers of the WFM locals met and planned a massive show of force for April 29.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] On April 29, 250 union members seized a train in Burke, northeast of Wallace; the engineer, Levi "Al" Hutton, later claimed at gunpoint.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] At each stop through Burke Canyon, more miners climbed aboard.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] At Frisco, the train stopped to load eighty wooden boxes, each containing fifty pounds (23 kg) of dynamite.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] At Gem, 150 to 200 more miners climbed onto three freight cars which had been added to the train.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] In Wallace, 200 miners were waiting, having walked seven miles (11 km) from Mullan.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] About a thousand men rode the train to Wardner, the site of a $250,000 mill of the Bunker Hill mine.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Witnesses later testified that the majority of those on the train knew nothing of any planned violence when they started out; they thought that it would be just a massive demonstration to intimidate the mine owners into recognizing the union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] However, the union had distributed masks and firearms to between 100 and 200 of the men, who acted as if under military discipline.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] "At no time did the demonstration assume the appearance of a disorganized mob.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Young, who had been elected with union support, had ridden to Wardner on the train with the union miners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] At Wardner, Young climbed atop a rail car, and ordered the group to disperse.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] His order was ignored, and he later said that any further attempt to restrain the miners would have been suicidal.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] State prosecutors claimed that Young had been paid off by the WFM.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Word had reached Wardner by telephone that the union miners were on their way, and most of the mine and mill workers had fled.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The crowd ordered the remaining workers out of the Bunker Hill mine and mill.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Once out, they were ordered to run, and some shots fired at them as they ran.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] James Cheyne was shot in the hip, then union miners shot more bullets into him as he lay on the ground; he died shortly after.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] One union man, John Smith, also called Schmidt, was mistakenly shot to death by other union men.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] After carrying three thousand pounds (1,400 kg) of dynamite into the mill, the blast completely destroyed the mill.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The crowd also burned down the company office, the boarding house, and the home of the mine manager.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The miners re-boarded the "Dynamite Express" and returned the way they came.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] At the Idaho governor's request, President William McKinley sent in the Army.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The majority of army troops sent to the Coeur d'Alene were African American soldiers of the 24th Infantry Regiment, stationed in Spokane, Salt Lake City, and other western posts.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The 24th had distinguished itself in combat during the Spanish–American War, and was seen as one of the most disciplined Army units not then serving overseas.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Bill Haywood criticized the U.S. government's attempts to turn whites against blacks.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Haywood wrote: "it was a deliberate attempt to add race prejudice ... race prejudice had been unknown among the miners." Nevertheless, he wrote that the government's efforts weren't all that successful, as the miners' turn against the army outweighed any racial dispute.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] State authorities used the troops to round up 1,000 men and put them into "the bullpen".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The arrests were indiscriminate; Governor Steunenberg's representative, state auditor Bartlett Sinclair believed that all the people of Canyon Creek had a "criminal history", and "the entire community, or the male portion of it, ought to be arrested".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The soldiers searched every house, breaking down the door if no one answered.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Mass arrests began on May 4, when 128 were arrested.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] More than two hundred were arrested the following day, and the arrests continued until about a thousand men had been arrested.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] What was called "the bullpen" was actually a number of structures.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The first 150 prisoners were kept in an old barn, a two-story frame structure 120 by 40 feet (37 by 12 m) and filled with hay.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] It was "still very cold in those altitudes" and the men, having been arrested with no opportunity to bring along blankets, "suffered some from the weather".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] As the barn became overcrowded, new prisoners were put in railroad boxcars.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] When both these became overcrowded, the prisoners were then forced to build a pine board prison for themselves, and it was surrounded by a six-foot barbed wire fence patrolled by armed soldiers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Conditions remained primitive, and three prisoners died.p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Army followed escaping miners into Montana and arrested them, returning them to Idaho, and failed to comply with jurisdictional or extradition laws.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] One man arrested and transported was a Montana citizen who had no connection to the Wardner events.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Two of the three county commissioners had been caught in the roundup, as had the local sheriff.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Later, a district court removed all of the county commissioners and the sheriff from office, charging that they'd neglected their official duties.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Most of those arrested were freed within two weeks.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] By May 12, 450 prisoners remained; by May 30, the number was 194.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Releases slowed, and 65 remained incarcerated on October 10;p.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] 37,40,73 the last prisoners in the bullpen were released in early December 1899.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Arrangements with replacement officials installed by Sinclair demonstrated "a pattern".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Subsequent research appears to have uncovered the apparent source of this assertion.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Steunenberg was later assassinated by Harry Orchard who claimed to have been hired by the WFM.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Thirty-four-year-old Paul Corcoran was the financial secretary of the Burke Miners Union and a member of the Central Mining Union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] While he had not been at the scene of the riot, Corcoran had been seen on the roof of a boxcar on the Dynamite Express, and at multiple union halls along the route, rallying men on to Wardner.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] He additionally told the Burke mine manager Mr.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Culbertson that his employees had left for the day and were on their way to Wardner, but would return in time for the night shift.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The prosecution, whose salaries were paid by a $32,000 grant from the mine owners, argued that Corcoran should take part of the blame for planning the attack on the Bunker Hill mill and Sullivan mine.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Corcoran was sentenced to seventeen years at hard labor.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Eight more miners and union leaders accused of leading the attack were scheduled for trial on charges of murder and/or arson, but bribed an army sergeant to allow them to escape.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Hundreds more remained in the makeshift prison without charges.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Meanwhile, Sinclair developed a permit system which would prevent mines from hiring any miner who belonged to a union.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The plan was designed to destroy the unions in the Coeur d'Alene district after the violence and lawlessness of the last 7 years.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Army endorsed the permit system verbally and in writing, resulting in considerable consternation at the McKinley White House.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The editor of one local newspaper, Wilbur H.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Stewart of the *Mullan Mirror*, dared to criticize the bullpen and its keepers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Sinclair appeared at his door alongside a major and several soldiers with unsheathed bayonets.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Stewart was taken to the bullpen, where he was assigned to garbage and latrine duty.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] However, the paper did not stop publication; Stewart's young wife, Maggie, continued to publish the weekly.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Sinclair impounded her type, and she contracted with another sympathetic publisher to continue the news.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Eventually Stewart was released under instructions to end the criticism.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Many populist elected officials in Shoshone County were rounded up for their support of the miners.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] The town sheriff of Mullan, Idaho was arrested and sent to the bullpen.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] May Arkwright Hutton, whose husband was the engineer on the dynamite express, wrote a book, *The coeur d' alenes: or, A Tale of the Modern Inquisition in Idaho*, about the treatment of the miners, and her husband, at the hands of the mine owners and the sheriff.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Both Huttons and Ed Boyce, head of the Western Federation of Miners, had invested in the Hercules silver mine before the 1899 war.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] After they had become wealthy mine owners, May Hutton sought to buy back all copies of her book.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1899-coeur-d-alene-labor-confrontation] Ed Boyce quit the miners union to manage a hotel in Portland.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A race riot took place in Detroit, Michigan, from the evening of June 20 through to the early morning of June 22, 1943.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] It occurred in a period of dramatic population increase and social tensions associated with the military buildup of U.S. participation in World War II, as Detroit's automotive industry was converted to the war effort.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Existing social tensions and housing shortages were exacerbated by racist feelings about the arrival of nearly 400,000 migrants, both African-American and White Southerners, from the Southeastern United States between 1941 and 1943.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The migrants competed for space and jobs against the city's residents as well as against European immigrants and their descendants.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The riot escalated after a false rumor spread that a mob of white people had thrown a black mother and her baby into the Detroit River.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Black people looted and destroyed white property as retaliation.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White people overran Woodward to Veron where they proceeded to violently attack black community members and tip over 20 cars that belonged to black families.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The Detroit riot was one of five that summer; it followed others in Los Angeles; Beaumont, Texas; and Mobile, Alabama, and preceded that of New York City.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The rioting in Detroit began among youths at Belle Isle Park on June 20, 1943; the unrest spread to other areas of the city and was exacerbated by false rumors of racial attacks in both the black and white communities.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] It was suppressed after 6,000 federal troops were ordered into the city to restore peace.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A total of 34 people were killed, 25 of them black and most at the hands of the white police force, while 433 were wounded (75 percent of them black), and property valued at $2 million (worth $30.4 million in 2020) was destroyed.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Most of the riot took place in the black area of Paradise Valley, the poorest neighborhood of the city.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] At the time, white commissions attributed the cause of the riot to black people and youths, but the NAACP claimed deeper causes: a shortage of affordable housing, discrimination in employment, lack of minority representation in the police, and white police brutality.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A late 20th-century analysis of the rioters showed that the white rioters were younger and often unemployed (characteristics that the riot commissions had falsely attributed to black people despite evidence to the contrary).
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] If working, the white people often held semi-skilled or skilled positions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White people traveled long distances across the city to join the first stage of the riot near the bridge to Belle Isle Park, and later some traveled in armed groups explicitly to attack the black neighborhood in Paradise Valley.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The black participants were often older, established city residents, who in many cases had lived in the city for more than a decade.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They also looted and destroyed white-owned property in their neighborhood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] By 1920, Detroit had become the fourth-largest city in the United States, with an industrial and population boom driven by the rapid expansion of the automobile industry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Detroit was unique among northern cities by the 1940s for its exceptionally high percentage of Southern-born residents, both black and white.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In this era of continuing high immigration from southern and eastern Europe, the Ku Klux Klan (KKK) in the 1920s established a substantial presence in Detroit during its early 20th-century revival.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The KKK became concentrated in midwestern cities rather than exclusively in the south.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] It was primarily anti-Catholic and anti-Jewish in this period, but it also supported white supremacy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The KKK contributed to Detroit's reputation for racial antagonism, and there were violent incidents dating from 1915.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Its lesser-known offshoot, Black Legion, was also active in the Detroit area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In 1936 and 1937, some 48 members were convicted of numerous murders and attempted murders, thus ending Black Legion's run.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Both organizations stood for white supremacy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Soon after the U.S. entry into World War II, the automotive industry was converted to military production; high wages were offered, attracting large numbers of workers and their families from outside of Michigan.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The new workers found little available housing, and competition among ethnic groups was fierce for both jobs and housing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] With Executive Order 8802, President Franklin D.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Roosevelt on June 25, 1941, had prohibited racial discrimination in the national defense industry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Roosevelt called upon all groups to support the war effort.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The executive order was applied irregularly, and black people were often excluded from numerous industrial jobs, especially more skilled and supervisory positions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In 1941, Detroit's Black population numbered nearly 150,000 of the total population of 1,623,452.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This total population would reach nearly 2 million by 1943, absorbing more than 400,000 white people and some 50,000 black migrants, mostly from the American South.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This second wave of the African American Great Migration was driven by the economic and political repression across the South exacerbated by the Great Depression and codified in Jim Crow laws respectively.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] These more recent African American arrivals were driven by de facto segregation and redlining to the already established Black community in the poor and overcrowded east side of the city.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A 60-block area east of Woodward Avenue was known as Paradise Valley and had aging and substandard housing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White American migrants came largely from agricultural areas and especially rural Appalachia, carrying with them southern prejudices.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Rumors circulated among ethnic white groups to fear African Americans as competitors for housing and jobs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Indeed, Black residents had to compete for low-level jobs with numerous European immigrants or their descendants, in addition to rural southern white people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Black families were excluded from all of the limited public housing except the Brewster Housing Projects and were exploited by landlords and forced to pay rents two to three times higher than those paid by families in the less densely populated white districts.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Like other poor migrants, they were generally limited to the oldest, substandard housing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] By the summer of 1943, after the United States had entered World War II, tensions between the white and black communities in Detroit were escalating; resistance to economic and political repression as well as the oppression and violence of the mostly white Detroit Police Department grew steadily.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] After the Civil War, slavery became illegal.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Former slaves and their descendants still faced severe discrimination.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] As a result, many former slaves could only find low paying work in agriculture or domestic service.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Southern black people migrated north in the 20th century in hopes of leaving the oppressive culture in the South.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] During the Civil War, Detroit was an important stop on the Underground Railroad, as many settled in the northern city or used it as a means to get to Canada.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] During World War II, it was sought out as a refuge for black people seeking to escape the lingering effects of the Jim Crow era.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The promise of employment and escape from the violent racial tensions in the South drew in many African American workers to the North.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Before the war, black workers in Detroit were scarce: even in 1942, 119 of 197 Detroit manufacturers surveyed did not have any black employees.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] However, by 1943, Detroit's labor shortage had become so severe that companies finally began employing African Americans.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A report in 1944 showed that with the 44% increase of wartime employment, black employment increased by 103%.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Ford Motor Company was the leading manufacturer in black employment: half of all black people in the auto industry in the U.S. were employed by Ford, and 12% of all Ford workers were black.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Ford made sure to develop close ties with African Americans, being in contact with leading clergy at major black churches and using ministers as a screening process to obtain recommendations for the best potential workers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This ensured that Ford only employed reliable long-term workers who would be willing to do the most labor-intensive jobs.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Around 1910, Ford gave a salary of $5 per day to its workers, which is equivalent to $162 per day in 2023.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Because of the city's growth in population and employment opportunities, Detroit became a symbol of cultural rebirth.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The statement "when I die, bury me in Detroit" became popular among the black community for these reasons.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The effect of World War II in Europe and Asia was felt heavily in the U.S. even before the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The defense industry was growing rapidly because the country was immersed in a military buildup to provide assistance to their European and Asian allies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] On the home front, African-Americans were subjected to low-level jobs with little security or protection against the discrimination and prejudice they faced in the work place.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Philip Randolph and other civil rights leaders took this opportunity to speak with President Roosevelt about expanding opportunities for African-Americans by outlawing discrimination in the defense industry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] At first, the president was hesitant to agree because of his political alignments but changed his mind when Randolph threatened a large march on the nation's capital.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] After Roosevelt signed Executive Order 8802 which prohibited racial discrimination within the defense industry, he was then preoccupied with providing adequate housing for the new additions to the workforce.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Housing in many cities was substandard, especially for people of color.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Housing in Detroit was strained as both black people and white people moved from southern states to Detroit to work in the booming manufacturing industry in the city.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] African-Americans were unable to buy houses in the suburbs during the majority of the 20th century because of racially biased practices, such as redlining and restrictive covenants.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They had no choice but to live in substandard housing in downtown Detroit in an area more commonly known as Black Bottom.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Properties in the city had high values for what residents were getting: single-family apartments crowded with multiple families, outstanding maintenance and, in many cases, no indoor plumbing.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The influx of African-Americans to Detroit exacerbated racial tensions already present in the city and culminated at the introduction of the Sojourner Truth Housing Project.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In 1941, in an attempt to lessen the severity of the housing crisis, the federal government and the Detroit Housing Commission (DHC) approved the construction of the Sojourner Truth Project with 200 units for black defense workers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The original location for this housing project was chosen by the DHC to be in the Seven Mile-Fenelon neighborhood in northeast Detroit.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They believed that this location would be uncontroversial because of its proximity to an already existing African-American neighborhood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] However, this decision was met with immense backlash.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White residents in the surrounding area formed an improvement association, the Seven Mile-Fenelon Improvement Association, and they were soon joined by the residents of the middle-class African American neighborhood, Conant Gardens.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] These two groups formed an alliance and organized the resistance to the Sojourner Truth Project.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] These groups protested by meeting with city officials, sending thousands of angry letters to the government and lobbying with their congressmen against the project, among other things.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Since the Federal Housing Administration (FHA) refused to insure any mortgage loans in the area after the announcement of the project, many of the residents in the area believed that this project would decrease nearby property values and reduce their ability to build on nearby vacant lots.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] On the other side, civil rights groups and pro-public housing groups rallied for the federal government to keep its promise to allow black residents in Sojourner Truth housing and address the housing shortage.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] There was only one other housing project in the city for African Americans at this time.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In response to the uproar in the local community, the federal government changed its decision on the racial occupancy of the housing project multiple times.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In January 1941, the DHC and federal officials declared that Sojourner Truth would have white occupants, but quickly decided instead that it would be occupied by black war workers just two weeks later.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Ultimately, it was decided that the Sojourner Truth project would house black residents as originally promised, much to the frustration of the local white community.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] As the first African-Americans workers and their families attempted to move into their new homes in February 1942, large crowds of both black supporters and white opponents surrounded the area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A billboard announcing "We Want White Tenants in our White Community" with American flags attached was put up just before the families were to move in.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White residents protested the project in the name of "protecting" their neighborhoods and property value.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] These efforts continued throughout the day as more people attempted to move in and tensions continued to rise.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] More than a thousand people showed up that day, and fighting erupted between the supporters and opponents.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Over a dozen police came onto the scene, but the situation worsened.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The fighting resulted in over 40 injured and 220 arrested.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Of those arrested, 109 were held for trial, only three of whom were white.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Detroit officials postponed the movement of African-Americans defense workers into the housing project in order to keep the peace.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This created a problem for the workers who did not have any place to live.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The one other public housing that housed black people was able to take up some of the residents, but many others had to find housing in other places.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] After about 2 months protesting had reduced, and Detroit Mayor Edward Jeffries called the Detroit police and Michigan National Guard to escort and protect the African-American workers and their families as they moved into their new homes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In June 1943, Packard Motor Car Company finally promoted three black people to work next to white people in the assembly lines, in keeping with the anti-segregation policy required for the defense industry.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In response, 25,000 white people walked off the job in a wildcat strike at Packard, effectively slowing down the critical war production.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Although white people had long worked with black people in the same plant, many wanted control of certain jobs and did not want to work right next to black people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Harold Zeck remembers seeing a group of white women workers coming into the assembly line to convince the white men workers to walk out of work to protest black women using the white women's bathroom.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Zeck remembers one of the women saying "They think their fannies are as good as ours." The protest ended when the men refused to leave work.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] There was a physical confrontation at Edgewood Park.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In this period, racial riots also broke out in Los Angeles, Mobile, Alabama and Beaumont, Texas, mostly over similar job issues at defense shipyard facilities.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Altercations between youths started on June 20, 1943, on Belle Isle, an island in the Detroit River.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] In what is considered a communal disorder, youths fought intermittently through the afternoon.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The brawl eventually grew into a confrontation between groups of white people and black people on the long Belle Isle Bridge, crowded with more than 100,000 day trippers returning to the city from the park.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] From there the riot spread into the city.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Sailors joined fights against black people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The riot escalated in the city after a false rumor spread that a mob of white people had thrown a black mother and her baby into the Detroit River.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White people overran Woodward Avenue to East Vernor Highway, where they proceeded to tip over 20 cars that belonged to black families.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The white people also started to loot stores while rioting.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Johnson argues that this rumor reflected black male fears about historical white violence against black women and children.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] An equally false rumor that black people had raped and murdered a white woman on the Belle Isle Bridge swept through white neighborhoods.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Angry mobs of white people spilled onto Woodward Avenue near the Roxy Theater around 4 a.m. on June 21, in the actual area of Brush Park beating black people as they were getting off street cars on their way to work.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They also went to the black neighborhood of Paradise Valley, one of the oldest and poorest neighborhoods in Detroit, attacking black civilians who were trying to defend their homes.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Black people attacked white-owned businesses.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Black people were outnumbered by a large margin and suffered many more deaths, personal injuries, and property damage.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The riots lasted three days and ended only after Mayor Jeffries and Governor Harry Kelly asked President Roosevelt to intervene.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] He invoked the Insurrection Act of 1807 and ordered in federal troops.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] About 6,000 troops imposed a curfew, restored peace and occupied the streets of Detroit.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Of the approximately 600 persons injured, more than 75% were black people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The first casualty was a white civilian who was struck by a taxi.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Later, four young white males shot and killed a 58-year-old black civilian, Mose McKissick, who was sitting at the bus stop.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The triggerman, 16-year-old Aldo Trani, later said he shot Kiska since he "wanted to kill myself a Nigger." He and the rest of the group had hunted the city for black people prior to the murder.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Trani was convicted of manslaughter and sentenced to 5.5 years to 15 years in prison.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Two other youths were convicted, Armando Mastantuono and Ralph Tancredi.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Mastantuono was sentenced to 2.5 years to 15 years in prison, and Tancredi was sentenced to 1.5 years to 15 years in prison.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Trani was released from prison after serving 2.5 years due to police misconduct during the investigation against him.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A doctor went to a house call in a black neighborhood.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] He then was hit in the back of the head with a rock and beaten to death by black rioters.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A couple years after the riot, a monument was dedicated to this doctor at the streets of East Grand Boulevard and Gratiot Avenue.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Leaders on both sides gave different explanations for the violence, effectively blaming the other side.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] White city leaders, including the mayor, blamed young black hoodlums and repeatedly framed the events as being caused by outsiders, people who were unemployed and marginal.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Mayor Jeffries said, "Negro hoodlums started it, but the conduct of the police department, by and large, was magnificent." The Wayne County prosecutor believed that leaders of the NAACP were to blame as instigators of the riots.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Governor Kelly called together a fact finding commission to investigate and report on the causes of the riot.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Its mostly white members blamed black youths, "unattached, uprooted, and unskilled misfits within an otherwise law-abiding black community," and regarded the events as an unfortunate incident.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They made these judgments without interviewing any of the rioters, basing their conclusions on police reports, which were limited.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Other officials drew similar conclusions, despite discovering and citing facts that disproved their thesis.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Selling of the Recorder's Court Psychiatric Clinic conducted interviews with 100 black offenders.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] He found them to be "employed, well-paid, longstanding (of at least 10 years) residents of the city", with some education and a history of being law abiding.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] He attributed their violence to their southern heritage.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This view was repeated in a separate study by Elmer R.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Akers and Vernon Fox, sociologist and psychologist, respectively, at the State Prison of Southern Michigan.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Although most of the black men they studied had jobs and had been in Detroit an average of more than 10 years, Akers and Fox characterized them as unskilled and unsettled; they stressed the men's southern heritage as predisposing them to violence.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Additionally, a commission was established to determine the cause of the riot, despite the unequal amount of violence toward black people, the commission blamed the riot on black people and their community leaders.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Following the violence, Japanese propaganda officials incorporated the event into its materials that encouraged black soldiers not to fight for the United States.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They distributed a flyer titled "Fight Between Two Races".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The Axis powers publicized the riot as a sign of Western decline.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Walter White, head of the NAACP, noted that there was no rioting at the Packard and Hudson plants, where leaders of the UAW and CIO had been incorporating black people as part of the rank and file.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] These changes in the defense industry had been directed by executive order by President Roosevelt and had begun to open opportunities for black people.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] A late 20th-century analysis of the facts collected on the arrested rioters has drawn markedly different conclusions.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] It notes that the white people who were arrested were younger, generally unemployed, and had traveled long distances from their homes to the black neighborhood to attack people there.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Even in the early stage of the riots near Belle Isle Bridge, white youths traveled in groups to the riot area and carried weapons.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Later in the second stage, white people continued to act in groups and were prepared for action, carrying weapons and traveling miles to attack the black ghetto along its western side at Woodward Avenue.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Black people who were arrested were older, often married and working men, who had lived in the city for 10 years or more.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] They fought closer to home, mainly acting independently to defend their homes, persons or neighborhood, and sometimes looting or destroying mostly white-owned property there in frustration.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Where felonies occurred, white people were more often arrested for use of weapons and black people for looting or failing to observe the curfew imposed. white people were more often arrested for misdemeanors.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Marshall Rosenberg stated that one of the incidents that motivated him in developing nonviolent communication were the 1943 Detroit riots, which he experienced in his early life at 9 years old.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Radio producer, writer, and director William N.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Robson introduced his Peabody Award winning radio drama "An Open Letter on Race Hatred" broadcast on the CBS network on July 24, 1943.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] The drama is narrated by Jackson Beck, featuring Frank Lovejoy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Capeci, Jr. and Martha Wilkerson wrote a book about the Detroit Race Riot, called *Layered Violence: The Detroit Rioters of 1943*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] It also talks about how black people were considered hoodlums and the white people were known as hillbillies.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This book also covers the black people struggle for racial equality in World War II.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] This also explains the rioters to be the transforming figures of racial violence in the 20th century.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1943-detroit-race-riot] Elaine Latzman Moon gives a brief overview about the riot in her book *Untold Tales, Unsung Heroes : An Oral History of Detroit's African American Community, 1918-1967*.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The **1969 Greensboro uprising** occurred on and around the campuses of James B.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Dudley High School and North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University (A&T) in Greensboro, North Carolina, when, over the course of May 21 to May 25, gunfire was exchanged between student protesters, police and National Guard.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] One bystander, sophomore honors student Willie Grimes, was killed, although whether he was killed by police or protesters remains unknown.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The uprising was sparked by perceived civil rights issues at the segregated high school, when a popular student council write-in presidential candidate was denied his landslide victory allegedly because school officials feared his activism in the Black Power movement.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Starting on the campus of Dudley High School, the uprising spread to A&T campus where students had stood up in support of the Dudley protest.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Escalating violence eventually led to armed confrontation and the invasion of the A&T campus by what was described at the time as "the most massive armed assault ever made against an American university".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The uprising ended soon after the National Guard made a sweep of A&T college dormitories, taking hundreds of students into protective custody.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] While local officials blamed outside agitators, a report released by the North Carolina State Advisory Committee to the United States Commission on Civil Rights found that James B.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Dudley High School had an unjust system and suppressed dissent.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] They found the National Guard invasion reckless and disproportionate to the actual danger, and criticized local community leaders for failing to help the Dudley High School students when the issues first emerged.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Before events began to coalesce in the spring of 1969, the students at James B.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Dudley High School were already unhappy.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] They no longer believed that desegregation of the school system in Greensboro was a possibility.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Their school was the only school in the district to place restrictions on student attire or forbid students leaving campus for lunch.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] But the catalyst for their uprising was their failure to elect a student council president of their choice.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Even though he was not permitted on the ballot, the students attempted to place honor student Claude Barnes in the office of president as a write-in.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] A senior, Barnes had been politically active in his earlier years at the school, but was feared by school officials, who believed him a militant advocate of Black Power as a member of the Youth for the Unity of Black Society.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Barnes won the election with 600 votes, a landslide compared to the top official candidate who received 200.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] But the student body was informed on May 1 that Barnes would not be permitted to run.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The students of Dudley High turned for assistance to A&T.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] In the later 1960s, A&T was a center for the Black Power movement in the South.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] They took the Dudley students seriously.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On May 2, A&T students attempted to join discussions with school administrators, but their several attempts proved unsuccessful.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Angry response of the students began to build, with an increasing number of students boycotting classes, and armed police were seen in the vicinity of the school in riot gear.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On May 9, the school superintendent effectively disempowered the school's black principal, sending in a white administrator to try to quell the trouble.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Students made several attempts during this period to reach a peaceful resolution with school officials, but this administrator did not take a sympathetic or conciliatory approach to the students.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On May 19, events began to reach a head.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Police were called to deal with picketing, and, in the midst of alleged police misconduct, nine students were arrested.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Student response damaged the school and resulted in more student arrests, as well as student injuries.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On May 21, during school hours, students again assembled near the school.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Police were contacted when an official indicated seeing a weapon on one of the students.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Efforts by a school administrator to disperse the protesters peaceably failed when some students instead began throwing rocks through the windows of the school.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Police brought tear gas against student protesters, applying it over a larger area than may have been needed for the small percentage of students involved in the protest.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] In some cases—according to residential bystanders—they pursued and gassed students for blocks even as they attempted to flee.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Community members, some of whom were also affected by the tear gas canisters, began throwing rocks at police and cars, while students from Dudley High went again to A&T to appeal for assistance.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Early response to the situation at Dudley had been restricted to members of the newly-formed black activism group Student Organization for Black Unity, but the events of the day brought attention from the wider campus.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] A&T student activist Nelson Johnson reported 400 students marching on Dudley High.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] While at first violence was contained to tear gas and rocks, the shooting started shortly thereafter.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Johnson claims that the first gunfire was instigated by a carload of young white people who fired onto the A&T campus, prompting the students to defend themselves in kind.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Police reported sniper fire from the dormitories at 10:45 p.m.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Wherever it started, the police began returning fire within two hours, and 150 National Guard were sent to the scene to keep the peace.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] One of them, bystander Willie Grimes, was killed, although whether he was shot by police or protesters remains unknown.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The 22-year-old Grimes had been walking with a group of friends to a restaurant at around 1:30 a.m. when shots came from a passing car.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Whether or not the car was a police vehicle has long been the subject of dispute.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] A state of emergency was declared in Greensboro and 500 more National Guardsmen were called in.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The university was closed down, and a curfew was set for 8p.m. to 5 a.m.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] During the day of May 22, violence continued, as protesters vented their anger on white motorists, overturning cars and attacking at least one of the drivers.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] A UPI reporter wrote that "it looked like war".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On information suggesting students may be harboring a large number of guns, then-governor Robert W.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Scott ordered the invasion of the dormitory Scott Hall, the centerpoint of the shooting.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] At approximately 7:00 a.m., supported by smoke, "nausea" and tear gas grenades, the National Guard swept through the dorm, placing the students they found under protective custody and doing tens of thousands worth of dollars in damage.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Many of the students were packing to evacuate or sleeping at the time of the invasion.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Over 300 students from Scott Hall and neighboring dormitories were sent to state prisons, where they were detained through the day.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] More than 60 bullet holes left their mark on Scott Hall.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Students alleged that during the sweep, personal items disappeared.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] When the sweep was completed, only three operable firearms had been located.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] By the 24th, the violence was contained.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The curfew was lifted and the National Guard withdrawn.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] The uprising was declared over on May 25.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Willie Grimes' funeral was attended by 2,000 people, and a marker was erected on campus in his memory.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Governor Scott stated that the violence had been incited by a group of hard-core militants who had seized on the high school election as a catalyst for furthering their own cause.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] On October 3 and 4 of that year, meetings were held to investigate the incident under the direction of the North Carolina State Advisory Committee to the United States Commission on Civil Rights.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] While local officials continued blaming "outsiders" and "radicals" for the event, the committee found that the "prevailing system" at Dudley was unjust and that the school had suppressed dissent.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] In 1979, Jack Elam, Greensboro's mayor during the event, expressed discomfort with the sweep of Scott Hall, but—although he agreed that communication had been poor—declared the committee's report a "joke".
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Johnson, who had been arrested for inciting the Dudley students to riot and who was instrumental in bringing the committee to review the situation, wrote later that the community ignored the Advisory Committee's report.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] Additional black policemen were employed by the city, although by 1979 the number of black policemen were still not representative of the proportion of black residents of the area.
[src:1855-fiji-expedition/1969-greensboro-uprising] 2008 saw the release of a documentary recounting the event, *Walls that Bleed*.
